    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, our offensive engine is headlined by **Vinnie Pasquantino** (72.92) and **Seiya Suzuki** (72.33), both of whom leverage significant matchup advantages into elite daily projections. **Vinnie Pasquantino** is the highest-rated start due to a favorable dynamic platoon split against Tanner Bibee, bolstered further by wind conditions that amplify his power profile. Meanwhile, **Seiya Suzuki** benefits from a soft matchup against Chase Petty (6.57 xERA), providing a rare high-floor, high-ceiling combination. We are also leaning heavily on **Mickey Moniak** (69.90), whose home-park profile provides a substantial boost, though we must keep a close eye on the 34% rain risk in his contest; a delay could compress his actual output despite the favorable raw metrics.\n\nThe most difficult decision on our bench was leaving **Trevor Story** (45.98) on the outside looking in. While his base projection remains respectable, the gauntlet of facing an elite arm like Tarik Skubal (2.76 xERA) significantly suppressed his utility score, as Skubal\u2019s ability to neutralize base-stealers negates the stolen-base equity we crave. We similarly opted for **Brice Turang** (61.75) over **Austin Riley** (42.29) because of the superior matchup context against Kyle Leahy. With **Josh Naylor** (70.19) anchoring the heart of the order against JR Ritchie, we are prioritizing volume and matchup efficiency over the raw pedigree of our bench reserves. **Jose Caballero** remains in the lineup despite a poor platoon split because his potential for stolen bases\u2014a category we are aggressively chasing\u2014remains vital, even if his floor is mitigated by the 9th-order slot.",
